      "id":"money/2013/nov/05/help-to-buy-small-lenders-big-banks-95-mortgages",
      "sectionId":"money",
      "sectionName":"Money",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-11-05T11:21:31Z",
      "webTitle":"Seeking Help to Buy? Think small lenders over big banks",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/money/2013/nov/05/help-to-buy-small-lenders-big-banks-95-mortgages",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/money/2013/nov/05/help-to-buy-small-lenders-big-banks-95-mortgages",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"The first batch of 95% mortgage rates announced under Help to Buy have been underwhelming, but there are good deals if you look beyond the major lenders",
        "headline":"Seeking Help to Buy? Think small lenders over big banks",
        "body":"<p>The launch of the second wave of the government's Help to Buy mortgage scheme a month ago means homebuyers with small deposits now have a wider choice of mortgages – but while the focus has been on 95% loans offered through the scheme, better deals have been cropping up elsewhere.</p><p></p><p>Help to Buy encourages lenders to offer 95% LTV mortgages by giving them a taxpayer-backed guarantee for 15% of the mortgage, protecting the bank if the borrower defaults. It was hoped this would allow lenders to grant applicants the same rates as if they had a 20% deposit, but the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/money/2013/oct/08/help-to-buy-mortgage-rates-disappoint-buyers\" title=\"First Help to Buy mortgage rates disappoint housebuyers\">handful of deals announced so far have been a bit of a letdown</a>, with Royal Bank of Scotland/NatWest and Halifax charging borrowers between 4.99% and 5.49%.</p><p></p><p>What it has done, though, is spurred some smaller lenders into action. <a href=\"http://www.cambridgebs.co.uk/\" title=\"Cambridge BS website\">Cambridge Building Society</a> has just unveiled a \"stepped rate\" discount mortgage which charges a variable rate of just 3.99% to first-time buyers with a 5% deposit. This rate lasts for the first year, then climbs to 4.89% for the final two years of the three-year deal. The society only lends within the following counties: Cambridgeshire, Norfolk, Suffolk, Essex, Hertfordshire, Buckinghamshire, Bedfordshire and Northamptonshire. For existing borrowers moving away from one of those regions, however, it will lend across England and Wales.</p><p></p><p><a href=\"http://www.thehanley.co.uk/\" title=\"Hanley Economic BS website\">Hanley Economic Building Society</a>, which lends across England and Wales, is offering a two-year fixed rate at 4.89% up to 95% LTV, available to both first-time buyers and existing borrowers. Like many smaller lenders, Hanley shuns the strict \"computer says no\" lending criteria adopted by the big banks. Head of operations David Lowndes says: \"We underwrite all our loans individually rather than relying on mechanistic credit scoring, and have approved 85% of applications in the past year.\"</p><p></p><p>The <a href=\"http://www.cbonline.co.uk/\" title=\"Clydesdale bank website\">Clydesdale</a> and <a href=\"http://www.ybonline.co.uk/\" title=\"Yorkshire bank website\">Yorkshire</a> banks have launched a three-year fixed rate for first-time buyers charging 4.99% up to 95% LTV with no arrangement fee. <a href=\"http://www.hrbs.co.uk/\" title=\"Hinckley  Rugby BS website\">Hinckley &amp; Rugby Building Society</a> offers a two-year discount mortgage at 5.09% to 95% LTV, with fees totalling £990.</p><p></p><p>These deals all undercut the Halifax Help to Buy two-year fixed rate priced at 5.19%, which also carries a £995 product fee, and they are notably cheaper than the five-year fix from RBS and NatWest, which charges a pricey 5.49% at 95% LTV, albeit with no fee.</p><p></p><p>Mark Harris, chief executive of mortgage broker SPF Private Clients, says the Help to Buy rates are disappointing, especially since lenders have a government guarantee behind them. \"It is worth looking beyond the scheme, especially if you can get help from the Bank of Mum &amp; Dad,\" he says.</p><p></p><p>The <a href=\"http://www.woolwich.co.uk/mortgages/first-time-buyer-mortgages.html\" title=\"Woolwich website\">Woolwich Family Springboard</a> allows you to buy a property with a 5% deposit, provided a family member can place a further 10% in a linked savings account. After three years the \"helper\" gets their money back, plus interest of 2% a year. The Springboard rate has just been cut from 3.99% to just 3.69%, fixed for three years and with no application fee. \"Guarantors must be aware of the risks, because their savings may be used to cover any shortfall if the buyer defaults on their loan,\" Harris says.</p><p></p><p>Lloyds' <a href=\"http://www.lloydsbank.com/mortgages/offers/lend-a-hand.asp\" title=\"Lloyds Lend a Hand mortgage\">Lend a Hand mortgage</a> is available to first-time buyers with a 5% deposit, provided a family member deposits another 20% into a savings account. The mortgage is a three-year fix at 3.34%, and Lloyds pays the saver a fixed 2.7% for three-and-a-half years.</p><p></p><p><a href=\"http://www.ybs.co.uk/\" title=\"Yorkshire BS website\">Yorkshire</a>, <a href=\"http://www.newbury.co.uk/\" title=\"Newbury BS website\">Newbury</a> and <a href=\"http://www.mhbs.co.uk/\" title=\"Market Harborough website\">Market Harborough</a> building societies also allow parents to offset their savings to secure a lower interest rate for their kids. \"<a href=\"http://www.nationwide.co.uk/savings/limited_access/savetobuy/introduction.htm\" title=\"Nationwide website\">Nationwide's Save to Buy scheme</a> is another option,\" says Adrian Anderson, director of mortgage broker Anderson Harris. \"If you pay £50 a month into a special savings account for a minimum six months, you can borrow to 95% LTV at 5.59% for three years, with a £499 fee.\"</p><p></p><p>If you're looking at 95% of a property's value you must be aware of the risks, Anderson says. \"If house prices fall, you could quickly find yourself in negative equity, although this is only really an issue if you need to remortgage or move.\"</p><p></p><p>You should also make sure you can still afford your repayments when interest rates finally rise, as is likely in the next two or three years, Anderson adds.</p><p></p><p>Help to Buy rates should fall from January next year as more lenders launch deals, says Brian Murphy, head of lending at the <a href=\"http://www.mortgageadvicebureau.com/\" title=\"Mortgage Advice Bureau website\">Mortgage Advice Bureau</a>. Virgin Money and Santander are among those to have announced that they will offer home loans under the scheme. \"But for now, you may find a cheaper 95% LTV mortgage from regional building societies,\" Murphy says. George Osborne and David Cameron have made a big noise about Help to Buy, but for now at least small is beautiful.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421690639|2013-11-05T11:22:54Z|e9ef6dcf2392b1d57f7f233605f0621bb19c08e1 -->",
