      "id":"money/2013/nov/04/parents-millennials-financial-advice-lesson",
      "sectionId":"money",
      "sectionName":"Money",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-11-04T19:44:30Z",
      "webTitle":"We're collecting the best (and worst) financial advice for millennials. Care to share?",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/money/2013/nov/04/parents-millennials-financial-advice-lesson",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/money/2013/nov/04/parents-millennials-financial-advice-lesson",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"Millennials, have your parents taught you how to save?",
        "headline":"We're collecting the best (and worst) financial advice for millennials. Care to share?",
        "body":"<p>Among the many lessons that parents are expected to impart on their offspring is how to manage a budget. Usually, they provide the first weekly allowance, the first piggy bank and the first trip to the bank for a savings account.</p> <p>But currently many parents of the so-called ‘millennial’ generation also face difficult decisions regarding money and their children. Among these: is it more important to <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/money/2013/oct/29/retirement-savings-small-steps\">save for retirement or college</a>? Should parents push college-age kids to live within their means and attend colleges with affordable tuitions, or should kids attend their dream schools even if it means being saddled with debt for many years post-graduation?</p> <p>As <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/money/us-money-blog/2013/oct/01/us-student-loans-college-planning-problems\">US college loans debt surpasses $1 trillion</a>, millennials are beginning to rethink investing in college. A <a href=\"https://www.wellsfargo.com/press/2013/20130522_MorethanhalfofMillennials\">Wells Fargo survey</a>&nbsp;of 1,414 millennials conducted this past spring revealed that 31% regret attending college and paying tuition; they believe they would have been better off working. Furthermore, 57% don’t believe that going to a more expensive and prestigious college always outweighs going to a less expensive schools.</p> <p>As <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/money/2013/oct/23/young-people-unemployment-jobs-report-answers\">millennials struggle to find their footing</a> in the financial reality of 2013, it would be easy to blame parents for not properly preparing them for the fiscal realities of being an adult. More than half of millennials say that the greatest influence on how they view money comes from their parents. About 61% would turn to their parents for financial advice; however, only 46% would describe their parents as savers.</p> <p>And so, Guardian readers, we want to hear from you.&nbsp;Millennials and parents: what financial lessons have you learned (or wish you hadn't) from each other?&nbsp;</p> <p>Fill out the following form and we’ll contact you for an ongoing project on millennial finance. Make sure you use your best prose. We may quote you!</p> <figure class=\"element element-embed\" data-alt=\"Form\"> <iframe src=\"https://docs.google.com/forms/d/179w8OlRhKQtdrGeWvytBp-nHp5UN6fpT5Ymk9cxPsBs/viewform?embedded=true\" width=\"460\" height=\"500\" frameborder=\"0\" marginheight=\"0\" marginwidth=\"0\">Loading...</iframe> </figure><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421640526|2013-11-05T11:22:54Z|855f5e06773df24a217f18e7af0ce77e06fdf29e -->",
