      "id":"money/2013/nov/04/broekn-steering-renault-rac",
      "sectionId":"money",
      "sectionName":"Money",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-11-04T07:01:01Z",
      "webTitle":"Broken steering on a trip to France left us going round in circles with the RAC ",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/money/2013/nov/04/broekn-steering-renault-rac",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/money/2013/nov/04/broekn-steering-renault-rac",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"10",
        "trailText":"<p>The car was repaired with non-Renault parts and it will cost £500 to put right</p>",
        "headline":"Broken steering on a trip to France left us going round in circles with the RAC",
        "body":"<p><strong>While holidaying in France our Renault Espace car broke down. We contacted the RAC, which arranged for us to be picked up and towed to a garage of its choice. The fault was identified as a broken steering pump. After several days a new one was fitted, along with the corresponding belt kit, at a cost of more than £500.</strong></p><p><strong>When we picked up the repaired car, the steering felt heavy, but we assumed the stiffness was due to the new part, which would ease after time. However, when we returned to the UK two weeks later there was still no improvement, so we took the car to our regular garage which found that non-Renault parts had been fitted. This meant the power steering was not working properly. They have said it will cost another £500 to put right.</strong></p><p><strong>I called RAC to complain and was told that someone would contact me in a few days. I had no reply. So I called and spoke to a lady who apologised profusely and said someone would definitely call me back in three days and gave me a reference, just in case. I have now contacted the RAC six times but to no avail. Can you help? </strong><em>HH, London</em></p><p>We have seen a noticeable increase in complaints about the RAC in recent months, but we are not sure this one is entirely merited. Leaving aside the fact that the (private-equity owned) recovery service failed to respond to you six times, which is very poor, we don't feel you can hold the RAC responsible for the French garage's shoddy work.</p><p>The RAC is there to recover you to a local garage in the event of a breakdown, which it did, alongside providing a replacement car and hotel. It didn't oversee the actual work and therefore cannot really be held responsible for the repairs carried out. A spokesman for the RAC confirmed as much to us.</p><p>Your dispute is with the garage in France. To complicate this story there is a suspicion that the pump may not have needed to be changed at all – it could be that just the belt had failed. Foreign travellers have long been taken advantage of by garages in this way.</p><p>Your best bet, given that you paid by credit card, is to try to make a claim against your card provider for the reasons stated in the first letter.</p><p>Alternatively, the European Consumer Centre (UKECC.net) will advise you on how to bring a cross-border claim against the garage in France, although the card option will be much the easier option.</p><p> <strong>We welcome letters but cannot answer individually. Email us at </strong><a href=\"mailto:consumer.champions@theguardian.com\" title=\"consumer.champions@theguardian.com\"><strong>consumer.champions@theguardian.com</strong></a><strong> or write to Consumer Champions, Money, the Guardian, 90 York Way, London N1 9GU. Please include a daytime phone number</strong></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421223503|2013-11-05T11:22:54Z|0a8361a6eb8085cd8ce54907f4ef8e09c75df872 -->",
