      "id":"money/2013/nov/01/supermarket-wine-tesco-sainsburys-asda",
      "sectionId":"money",
      "sectionName":"Money",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-11-01T13:02:36Z",
      "webTitle":"Supermarket wine sales: wine rack or wine racket?",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/money/2013/nov/01/supermarket-wine-tesco-sainsburys-asda",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/money/2013/nov/01/supermarket-wine-tesco-sainsburys-asda",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"1",
        "trailText":"<p>You're in Tesco, Sainsbury's or Asda and the wine deals look too good to resist. But are those offers really what they seem?</p>",
        "headline":"Supermarket wine sales: wine rack or wine racket?",
        "body":"<p>If you are a typical supermarket shopper, chances are this weekend you will pop a bottle of wine into your trolley – and it will almost certainly be on discount and quite likely even half price. Nine in 10 of the bottles of wine we drink in the UK are bought from the major supermarket chains, and 60% of those are on discount. But are the half-price or two-for-a-tenner deals genuine?</p><p>Guardian Money asked mySupermarket.co.uk, which compares prices at all the major chains, to track the pricing on some of the major wine brands sold by the supermarkets over the past year – and found an extraordinary zig-zag pattern where prices are \"established\" at what critics say are artificially high levels to meet legal requirements, then cut to give shoppers the impression they are obtaining a bargain.</p><p>We also talked to industry insiders – including the former head of wine at Sainsbury's, who says many of the promotions are manufactured. Shoppers, he says, are being told a £5 bottle is \"half price\" when it was never worth £10. We found that even after a \"half price\" reduction, shoppers are sometimes paying more than they were being charged just a few months earlier.</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-421454748'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/MONEY/Pix/pictures/2013/11/1/1383309698591/Tesco2-001.jpg' alt='Tesco2' width='220' height='287' class='gu-image'/><figcaption></figcaption></figure><p>Take Tesco's Ogio Pinot Grigio, one of the supermarket's top selling wines. This weekend it is on sale at £5.49, marketed as half price, down from £10.99. The figures from mySupermarket show that Tesco priced the wine at £10.99 for just 63 out of the last 365 days. Indeed, for almost the same length of time – 58 days – the Ogio Pinot Grigio was on sale at Tesco for £4.99. Buyers of the \"half price\" wine this weekend are actually paying 50p more than they were in July this year.</p><p>Hardy's Legacy Shiraz at Tesco is another wine with extraordinary price movements. This weekend it is on half-price offer at £4.99, down from £9.99. It has jigged up and down from £9.99 to £4.99 several times over the past year, and in March was selling for just £4.</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-421454745'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/MONEY/Pix/pictures/2013/11/1/1383310517857/Sainsbury-001.jpg' alt='Sainsbury' width='220' height='287' class='gu-image'/><figcaption></figcaption></figure><p>It's a similar picture at Sainsbury's, where we tracked the price of its Mondelli and Montepulciano wines. This weekend it is marketing Toretta de Mondelli Pinot Grigio as \"Save 33%, was £7.99 now £5.32\". But it has only been priced at £7.99 for 16 days out of the last 365, according to the mySupermarket data. For 148 days out of the past year, and as recently as 23 September, Sainsbury's priced the same bottle at £4.99. Buyers this weekend, although getting a third off the most recent price, are paying 33p more than they were for much of the past year.</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-421454746'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/MONEY/Pix/pictures/2013/11/1/1383310386691/Asda-001.jpg' alt='Asda' width='220' height='287' class='gu-image'/><figcaption></figcaption></figure><p>Asda, which coined the slogan \"Always Low Prices\", also hikes and drops wine prices. It is telling shoppers this weekend that its Campo Viejo wine is on \"Rollback\" at just £6, down from £8.50. But at the start of the year it was £5, and has traded at £8.50 for just 85 days in the past year. Much of the rest of the time it has been at £5, £6 or £8.28. And if you are thinking about buying some Jacobs Creek wine at the store this weekend, currently priced at £7.50, you might want to hold off. Asda's Jacobs Creek Pinot Grigio has been £5 or £7.50 all year; given that it has spent October priced at £7.50, shoppers can perhaps expect it to be back at £5 pretty soon.</p><p>There is no suggestion the supermarkets are breaking any laws on price promotions. They meticulously stick to the rules on \"price establishment\" before they launch a cut-price deal. But critics say the half-price deals lure consumers into thinking they are receiving a bargain when it's nothing of the sort.</p><p>Allan Cheeseman joined Sainsbury's as a wine buyer in 1971 – when it was selling 76,000 bottles a week – and became its director of wine in 2000, by which time 3.5m bottles were passing through the tills. But since leaving the supermarket and becoming an industry consultant, he has spilled the pinot on pricing practices. He says: \"Some of the half-price offers at the supermarkets are blatantly manufactured. You will see a Mondelli or an Ogio on sale for a very high price for a period of time, then discounted massively. But I know what the supermarkets paid in the first place. The problem is that as a nation we have become promotion junkies.\"</p><p>A <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b006mg74/features/supermarket-wine-oz-clarke\" title=\"\">BBC Watchdog</a> programme aired in October found similar pricing issues to those highlighted by Guardian Money. Wine writer and broadcaster Oz Clarke said: \"The truth is that the only way to make a profit out of the wines they sell so much of, is if the wine was never worth more than £5 in the first place.\"</p><p>Ted Sandbach, founder of independent wine distributor the <a href=\"http://www.oxfordwine.co.uk\" title=\"\">Oxford Wine Company</a>, claims to have seen cynical pricing practices at first hand. \"I saw it on a trip to Australia with the wine buyer from one of the big supermarkets. The winemaker had a lot to offload, so the supermarket created a brand – the sort of thing that is labelled 'Crocodile Dundee' or the like – and priced it at £9.99 in some of its stores, then reduced it to a 'half price' £4.99, but still made a whacking big profit. Some people might call this clever marketing. I call it downright cheating.\"</p><p>We showed the mySupermarket data to the major supermarket chains and asked them to justify the zig-zag in wine pricing. Why does wine move up and down in price so much, given it's not seasonal produce, like fruit or vegetables? Are shoppers right to suspect that the supermarkets are cynically establishing prices at a high level only to manufacture half-price deals later?</p><p>Few answered the questions directly. In a statement Tesco said: \"Customers have repeatedly told us they really enjoy the variety and great value our wine selection offers, and both the Ogio and Hardy's wines are extremely popular. Our half-price wine offers remain popular, indicating customers are satisfied with both the quality and value for money.\"</p><p>Asda said: \"As Britain's lowest price supermarket our simple aim is always to offer the lowest prices for the longest,\" while Sainsbury's said: \"Wine prices are highly dependent on factors that vary – from harvest yields to transport costs and duties. We work hard to mitigate these and keep prices down, including offering price reductions and promotions whenever possible.\"</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-421454747'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/MONEY/Pix/pictures/2013/11/1/1383310445885/Waitrose-001.jpg' alt='Waitrose' width='220' height='287' class='gu-image'/><figcaption></figcaption></figure><p>Waitrose challenged the suggestion that its wine deals may not be genuine. To be fair to Waitrose, when Guardian Money went in search of wine promotion and deals at the retailer, it had fewer on offer than the other big chains. We picked the Robert Mondavi Woodbridge Chardonnay, on offer this weekend at £7.99, down from £9.99. As recently as mid-July, Waitrose was selling it for £7.49, and in April it cost £6.29, according to mySupermarket.</p><p>Waitrose disputed the figures, saying the mySupermarket prices did not align with its own records on 10 days out of the last 365. A spokeswoman said: \"This wine has been promoted three times in the last year and has been off promotion for 79% of the time … We believe one promotion every four months to be a good frequency and the wine offers real value at both its full selling price and promotional price. The price has been £9.99 for 127 days since May this year, which is not a short period increase. Costs from suppliers are confidential but it is worth noting that since the previous increase to £8.49 in June 2011 there have been two increases in duty.\"</p><p>Guardian Money did not cover Morrisons because mySupermarket obtains its data from supermarket delivery websites, and Morrisons does not offer an online buying service. Aldi does feature on mySupermarket, but doesn't use promotions to sell its wine. While we counted 73 wines in Tesco on some sort of deal, Aldi has none (although Aldi's three Pinot Grigios, at £3.99 to £4.39, are all priced lower than Tesco's cheapest deal).</p><p>We also shared our findings with Stella Creasy MP, the shadow consumer affairs minister. She said everyone loved a good deal, but it was clear some retailers were \"moving the goalposts\" in providing the information people need to help them choose.</p><p>\"We want supermarkets to compete to be the best at quality and value, not confusion and sleight of hand when it comes to marking up prices. Just as we've seen in other markets, such as those around the sale of furniture, there are lessons to be learned about how to ensure consumers have more information about just how good a bargain they are really getting before they fill their trolleys, so that they don't end up paying over the odds.\"</p><p>Not every supermarket wine offer should be treated with suspicion. In some cases, even the cynics say you should jump at the deal. Sandbach says he has found Moet &amp; Chandon on sale in Tesco at a lower price than he is offered by Moet as a wholesaler, while Cheeseman says wine quality has improved massively since the cheap plonk of the early 1970s, and that a lot of sub-£5 wines represent incredible value. \"It's actually quite difficult to buy a bad wine these days,\" he says.</p><p>But the days of a decent £5 wine are numbered, he claims, as on a £5 bottle of wine, £2 is duty and £1 is VAT. Once transport costs and the supermarket's mark-up are included, as little as 50p may be going to the vineyard. \"It's the £8-£10 market that is growing now. The three-for-£10 or under-£5 wines aren't going to be there,\"<strong> </strong>Cheeseman says.</p><p>Sandbach adds: \"In a £4.99 wine, only a few pence are going to the producer. But in a £7.99 wine, a lot more goes to the producer, and you are buying a much higher quality wine.\" As an independent retailer, he asks: \"Why do suppliers allow their product to be torn apart by constant promotions?\"</p><p>The answer may be that it won't happen for much longer, according to Cheeseman, who says the big producers are beginning to turn their noses up at the British supermarkets.</p><p>\"You can go to Castel [France's largest wine producer] and their turnover is more than the entire UK wine market,\" he says. \"A British supermarket might say, we are very important and we sell four million bottles a week, but globally Britain is slipping down the wine buying league. The suppliers are beginning to turn their back on the UK because of our arrogance and pricing.\"</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421391970|2013-11-05T11:22:54Z|7013df7454b912d5ad4f39ad2d9b58f1ffcdc1a9 -->",
