      "sectionId":"money",
      "sectionName":"Money",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-26T06:00:23Z",
      "webTitle":"Dear Jeremy – your work issues solved",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/money/2013/oct/26/dear-jeremy-work-issues-solved",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/money/2013/oct/26/dear-jeremy-work-issues-solved",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"8",
        "trailText":"Problems at work? Need advice? Our agony uncle – and readers – have the answer<br />• How can I spur my unemployed partner out of his apathy?<br />• Job interviews: at what stage is it okay to ask about salary?",
        "headline":"Dear Jeremy – your work issues solved",
        "body":"<h2><strong>How can I spur my unemployed partner out of his apathy?</strong></h2><p><strong>My partner has been unemployed for nine months and his apathy towards job hunting is driving me mad. How can I spur him on? I am convinced that in this climate he needs to do more than just apply for advertised posts on job websites, but for reasons I cannot understand he is reluctant to do anything beyond this, such as get unpaid work experience or network with professional or academic contacts.</strong></p><p><strong>He took voluntary redundancy in 2011 and returned to university, graduating with a master's in IT in January, and hopes to become a website designer for a firm. However, he has not had one interview and while his outlook has gone from unrealistic optimism to concern, he still refuses to take those extra steps.</strong></p><p><strong>Suggestions from me descend into arguments, with him feeling accused of not doing enough – which is probably fair. He does lack confidence, which I think is a factor.</strong></p><p><strong>He received a good redundancy payout so will be OK financially for another six months. I have tried taking a backseat to let him beat his own path, but the search grinds to a halt. I don't want to be his job counsellor; I just want him to put in the effort needed so we can get on with our lives.</strong></p><p></p><p><strong>Jeremy says</strong></p><p>I think it unlikely that your partner's reluctance to pull out all the stops is caused simply by apathy or laziness. I suspect it's something more complicated; not necessarily more admirable, but maybe a bit more manageable.</p><p>I think he finds failure extremely painful; failure challenges his self-belief and disturbs his vanity. You say that when he first started looking for a job, armed with his new master's in IT, his outlook was one of unrealistic optimism – but he then met nothing but rejection. To a more realistic person, early disappointment would have come as no surprise; to him it may have come as a serious shock.</p><p>There are many ways of dealing with rejection, but to oversimplify, you can adopt one of two extremes. It either intensifies your resolution and determination, or you shy away from further pain. You either redouble your efforts, or you find that so demeaning – and with such a high probability of further humiliation – that you shrink back. The irrational belief is, the less hard you try, the less it will hurt when you're yet again rebuffed. This is understandable and is human. So if you want to steer your partner into more enterprising ways, berating him – however tactfully – is unlikely to be effective. You're more likely to be successful if you appeal to his intelligence.</p><p>He knows he is clever and well-qualified. He knows there are jobs out there he could do extremely well and he knows that other people, less able than he, are getting those jobs. So work with him on concocting a plan based not on plain, dogged perseverance, but one that uses his intelligence and imagination, one than explores different, unconventional approaches. Encourage him to think of it as a way of outwitting the system. As a would-be web designer there should be plenty of opportunities to demonstrate his talents and enterprise. There is a very good chance that his enjoyment of this exercise will in itself lift his spirits and his sense of purpose.</p><p></p><p><strong>Readers say</strong></p><p>• He is solvent and has time available but is lacking experience; that's the ideal opportunity to start working for himself as a web designer. He could charge very competitive fees and use the experience to build up a portfolio if he doesn't want to remain self-employed.<strong> webweasel</strong></p><p></p><p>• Master's in IT, no job after nine months. His CV must be seriously deficient or his expectations too narrow. Find out what his peers are doing, as this is an indication of where his particular master's is valued. <strong>Burzmaili</strong></p><h2>Job interviews: at what stage is it okay to ask about salary?<br /></h2><p><strong>Many jobs are advertised with an \"attractive\" or \"competitive\" salary, with no specific figure mentioned. I, like most people, have certain financial commitments, so it would seem pointless to attend an interview for a job paying a wage that cannot cover these. This would be wasting both my time and the interviewer's. But at what stage of seeking a job is it permissible to ask about the salary on offer? How is the subject best broached at an early stage without it appearing that the only consideration is money?</strong></p><p></p><p><strong>Jeremy says</strong></p><p>However delicately you phrase the question, you risk alienating the prospective employer before they have even had a chance to size you up.</p><p>Remember that for most desirable jobs there will be at least a dozen fully qualified candidates, so interviewers will be looking for objective reasons to eliminate applicants. An applicant who asks about salary right at the start of the recruitment process could provide exactly such a reason – and not just, as you suggest, because the only consideration seems to be money. It also implies a lack of interest or curiosity and a willingness to forfeit the chance of a job before knowing anything about it.</p><p>Furthermore, the absence of even a guideline salary figure in the original advertisement might simply mean that the employer is prepared to be flexible; that if an outstanding candidate emerged, the salary could be negotiated to suit. In other words, even if you raised the subject, the employer might be unable to give you a definitive answer. You would have risked a big black mark with nothing useful gained.</p><p>While it might be \"pointless\" to attend an interview if it transpires that the maximum salary is well below your necessary minimum, you will never be certain ahead of the event. And you run the real risk of eliminating yourself needlessly from a job that might have suited you perfectly.</p><p>Make it absolutely clear from the beginning that you very much like the sound of the role on offer, that you would like to hear more about it, and why you think you might be the perfect match. If the employer agrees that you are a more suitable candidate than any of the others, discussions about salary levels are obviously much more likely to be to your liking.</p><p></p><p><strong>Readers say</strong></p><p>• The way it works is that the manager wants who he/she thinks is best and doesn't care what that person is paid – as long as it is less than they get. The upper constraint is set by HR or a more senior manager. I think the best approach is to concentrate on being a dazzling candidate at interview, one that the manager is prepared to make the extra effort for in terms of persuading HR and his/her boss that you merit a good salary. <strong>salamandertome</strong></p><p></p><p>• If you have done your research and know your industry you should already have some idea of the remuneration. Interview well, be the best candidate, and the salary will come up in the follow-up interviews. Then it's time to negotiate. <strong>hok011 </strong></p><p><strong>For Jeremy's and readers' advice on a work issue, send a brief email to </strong><a href=\"mailto:dear.jeremy@theguardian.com\" title=\"\"><strong>dear.jeremy@theguardian.com</strong></a><strong>. Please note that Jeremy is unable to answer questions of a legal or contractual nature or to reply personally.</strong></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420633418|2013-11-05T11:22:54Z|774726fd99bc870d7bbc9cc1c7a1077ed6510a5c -->",
